# Modular Architecture Rules

## Module principles

Every module must have:

- One clear responsibility
- Defined public interfaces
- Minimal dependencies
- Testable business logic
- No hidden cross-module state
- Clear ownership

## Approved layering

```
Presentation (UI)
    ↓
Application (controllers / state)
    ↓
Domain (use cases, models)
    ↓
Infrastructure (repositories, Firebase, HTTP)
```

Infrastructure must not control the domain model. Domain logic must not depend directly on Flutter widgets, WebView classes, Firebase UI objects, Unity scene objects, or HTTP framework request types.

## Feature isolation

Each feature should contain its own models, controllers/state, services, repositories, screens, widgets, and tests.

Example (player app):

```
features/game_catalogue/
├── data/
├── domain/
├── presentation/
└── tests/
```

Admin app uses `lib/modules/` per project convention.

## Shared code

Move code to shared modules only when:

- Used by multiple features
- Stable enough to generalize
- Free from feature-specific assumptions
- Clearly documented

Do not create an oversized `utils/` folder. Use focused categories: `validation`, `formatting`, `logging`, `networking`, `localization`.

## UI and data access

UI components must not communicate directly with Firestore for complex business operations. Use repositories and use cases.

## Circular dependencies

**Prohibited.** Use abstractions or shared domain contracts instead of cross-feature implementation imports.

## Review checklist

- [ ] Correct dependency direction
- [ ] No circular dependencies
- [ ] Business logic not in widgets or MonoBehaviours
- [ ] Shared code justified and documented
